nodes.name: SUAC_0
nodes.description: Seven bundles of spruce fibers wrapped together with plant stems and cordage. Part of acorn processing kit, used to sweep the interior hopper basked clean after acorns have been pounded.

nodes.description: Nine black and seven red bands on one end. Three red bands on other end with obsidian projectile point.

nodes.description: Five blue and four red bands on one end. Three blue bands and one red band on other end with obsidian point.

nodes.description: Arrow with six red and seven blue bands on one end with feathers; three red bands on other end with obsidian point (CC). Obsidian point attached with thin red threat/fibers; arrow becomes thinner as arrow shaft nears point (E. Kent, 04/03/2015).

nodes.description: Eight black and sevn red bands on one end. Three red bands and one black band at other end with obsidian point.

nodes.description: Eight red and seven black bands on one end with feather. Three red bands on other end with obsidian point.

nodes.description: Five blue and four blue bands on one end. Three blue bands and one red band on other end with obsidian point.

nodes.name: SUAC_19
nodes.description: Three black and six red bands on one end with feathers. One large blue band and two red bands at other end with obsidian point.

nodes.name: SUAC_20
nodes.description: Five blue and six red bands at one end. Two red bands and one blue band at other end with bone point.

nodes.name: SUAC_21
nodes.description: Five blue bands and seven red bands on one end. Two red bands and one blue band on other end with bone point.

nodes.name: SUAC_22
nodes.description: Five blue and seven red bands on one end. Two red bands and one blue band on other end with bone point.

nodes.name: SUAC_23
nodes.description: Five blue and ten red bands on one end. Two red and one blue band on other end with bone point. Object appears to have red pigment on bone point.

nodes.name: SUAC_24
nodes.description: Five blue and seven red bands on one end. Two red and one blue band on other end with notched section.

nodes.name: SUAC_25
nodes.description: Broken tip. Five blue bands, nine red bands at one end. Two red bands and one blue band at other end which is borken off.

nodes.name: SUAC_26
nodes.description: Arrow with broken point and no head. Five blue bands and nine red bands on one end. Two red and one blue band on other end which is broken off.

nodes.name: SUAC_27
nodes.description: Arrow without head. Plain wooden shaft with some darker bark (?). Notched at one end.

nodes.name: SUAC_28
nodes.description: Without head. Two red bands on one one broken end. Eight black bands and seven red bands at other end with notches but no projectile point.

nodes.name: SUAC_29
nodes.description: Without head. Plain wooden shaft. Notched on end.

nodes.name: SUAC_30
nodes.description: Without head. Five blue and nine red bands at one end. Other end plain. No head, no feathers.

nodes.name: SUAC_31
nodes.description: Rope to catch deer. Finely braided, with braided-in knot, similar to a simple noose. Approximately 1 cm thick.

nodes.name: SUAC_32
nodes.description: Elk horn wedge. Used to split wood. Long portion of horn, flat on one side. Some striations on the flat side, perhaps from cutting it in half.

nodes.name: SUAC_33
nodes.description: Tapered wedge taken from the base of an elk horn; outside polished with one side flat. Thin end slightly chipped. Used to split wood.

nodes.name: SUAC_34
nodes.description: Flaked red chert blade, hafted to a carved ash wood handle and bound with wrapped twine in "s" twist, cemented with asphaltum.

nodes.name: SUAC_36
nodes.description: Porcupine quills, dyed yellow, tightly braided around a vegetable fiber core, with a needle-like carved wooden stick attached to one end via thin twine or thread. May be detatched from Object ID 8922 or a similar item.

nodes.name: SUAC_38
nodes.description: One bundle of 25 straws tied together with a strip of cotton fabric with a red printed design on it. Straws may be a gaming set of counters, or could be raw materials for basket making.

nodes.name: SUAC_39
nodes.description: Die or gambling pieces made of nutshells, pitch, and beads; three to eight white glass seed beads inlayed in pitch in each die, some beads may be missing. Shells slightly cracked.

nodes.name: SUAC_43
nodes.description: Oval bone with rawhide tie and incised, pigmented cross-hatched triangles. Decorated scraper used to crush lice. Also incorrectly identified in museum records as a comb, ornament, and pendant.

nodes.name: SUAC_44
nodes.description: Woven cedar bark rope. Two strands wrapped together.

nodes.name: SUAC_45
nodes.description: Three-piece pump drill, used to bore holes in items. Carved disk, handle, polished shaft. Sharp metal tip, worn leather strap attached to handle. In good condition, fit for use. Shows much use on disk and shaft.

nodes.name: SUAC_46
nodes.description: Currently bundled and tied.

nodes.name: SUAC_47
nodes.description: Described as "Moqui" drill (CC) and pump drill (SEL) with stone point. Wooden drill with cloth rope, stone point, bound on with leather cord. Condition: broken and repaired.

nodes.name: SUAC_48
nodes.description: Used for tying deer. Three-stranded with loop in one end.

nodes.name: SUAC_49
nodes.description: Woven rope used for tying deer. Three-stranded with loop in one end.

nodes.name: SUAC_50
nodes.description: Wood and twine needle which has an open eye at each end of the shaft for easy threading.

nodes.name: SUAC_51
nodes.description: Very tightly twisted strands, thin twine. Two strands of twine cordage.

nodes.name: SUAC_52
nodes.description: Curved wooden bow concave side painted red and decorated with interspersed sets of navy blue parallel, horizontal lines. Padded hide strip grip in center, sewn in place. Bow is cracked horizontally across the back just above the grip. Sinew string in place; slack. (CC)

nodes.name: SUAC_53
nodes.description: Carved wooden bow; painted red on one side with a wound strip hide grip in the center and a twisted sinew string (still taught).

nodes.name: SUAC_54
nodes.description: Curved wooden bow decorated on concave face with red and turquoise horizontal stripes (22 turquoise and 14 red); wound, leather-strip grip in center. Twisted sinew string wound at both ends; string slack.

nodes.name: SUAC_55
nodes.description: Sinew-backed, birch wood bow with hide grip (unraveling); no decoration; sinew string still taught.

nodes.name: SUAC_57
nodes.description: Black-brown banded obsidian core obsidian from which many flakes have been taken, red and black. Same type of obsidian used for "dance money," ceremonial obsidian blades.

nodes.name: SUAC_58
nodes.description: Crushing stone, pestle. Greenish-colored stone, large base, tapers at midsection, flares at top, 2 chips off base.

nodes.name: SUAC_59
nodes.description: Crusher. Larger base, tapers in midsection, flares at top (but base is larger). Large chip in base.

nodes.name: SUAC_60
nodes.description: Phallic shaped stone pestle/pounder, greenish toned stone.

nodes.name: SUAC_61
nodes.description: Phallic shaped stone pestle/pounder; greenish toned stone

nodes.name: SUAC_62
nodes.description: Oval soapstone dish, rim broken in two places. Used for catching oil during cooking.

nodes.name: SUAC_63
nodes.description: Soapstone dish with rim worn in one spot. Elliptical shape, shallow.

nodes.name: SUAC_69
nodes.description: Salmon spear consisting of a wooden shaft and two detatchable spear heads. Carved wooden shaft, contracted at one end and wrapped with twine. Bone and dental material combined to form points tied by twine and cemented with asphaltum.

nodes.name: SUAC_70
nodes.description: A set of 45 slender wooden gambling sticks bundled together and secured with thread; one stick marked black in the middle. The game is called "Kin": the player holds up two sticks and his adversary guesses in which hand is the marked one.

nodes.name: SUAC_71
nodes.description: Dip net of iris root fiber twine with stone sinker.

nodes.name: SUAC_72
nodes.description: Woven fishing net used for catching salmon.

nodes.name: SUAC_73
nodes.description: Woven fishing net used for catching salmon

nodes.name: SUAC_75
nodes.description: Maple bark skirt.

nodes.name: SUAC_76
nodes.description: Birch wood bow with twine; painted plain red on convex face with red painted repeated decoration on concave face. Taught fiber string in place.

nodes.name: SUAC_77
nodes.description: Very large obsidian core from which many flakes have been taken. Same type of obsidian used for "dance money," ceremonial obsidian blades.

nodes.name: SUAC_78
nodes.description: String of dentalium shell beads strung lengthways.

nodes.name: SUAC_79
nodes.description: A money purse made of elk antler with decorative hide strips (some fur missing). Dentalium beads 8931.2 originally stored inside.

nodes.name: SUAC_83
nodes.description: A money purse made of elk antler and fur. Short segment of antler slit cut lengthwise. Fur wrapped around. Engraved with line. Triangles around slit.

nodes.name: SUAC_84
nodes.description: One bundle thinner sticks, separate bag with no ID tag. Straws may be a gaming set of counters, or could be raw materials for basket making.

nodes.name: SUAC_85
nodes.description: Two bundles of thicker, flatter sticks, same material, in one bag. Straws may be a gaming set of counters, or could be raw materials for basket making.

nodes.name: SUAC_86
nodes.description: Dentalia shell beads on broken iris root string, shell money. Originally in elk antler money purse 8931.1.
